<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How much hay should a horse eat per day?", answer: "A horse should eat 1.5% to 2% of its body weight in forage (hay or pasture) per day as a minimum. For a 1,000-pound horse, that is 15 to 20 pounds of hay daily. Horses in moderate to heavy work may need the higher end of this range. Forage should make up at least 50% of the total diet (by weight) to maintain healthy digestive function, as horses are designed to eat fibrous material continuously throughout the day." },
  { question: "When does a horse need grain in addition to hay?", answer: "Horses at maintenance (light riding or no work) generally do not need grain if they are receiving adequate quality hay and a vitamin/mineral supplement. Grain becomes necessary when energy demands exceed what forage alone can provide — typically at moderate or higher work levels. Horses in heavy training, competition, breeding mares, growing foals, and hard-keeping horses may need 0.5% to 1.2% of body weight in concentrate feed daily." },
  { question: "How much water does a horse need per day?", answer: "An average 1,000-pound horse drinks 5 to 10 gallons of water per day at maintenance. Water needs increase significantly with exercise, hot weather, and lactation — working horses may drink 15-20 gallons daily in summer. As a rule of thumb, provide 0.5 to 1 gallon per 100 pounds of body weight. Always provide unlimited access to clean, fresh water. Inadequate water intake is a leading cause of impaction colic." },
  { question: "Does my horse need a salt block or loose salt?", answer: "Yes, all horses need supplemental sodium chloride (salt) because hay and grain alone do not provide enough. A 1,000-pound horse needs approximately 1 to 2 ounces of salt per day at rest, and more during exercise or in hot weather. Loose salt is preferred over salt blocks because horses may not lick blocks enough to meet their needs. Many horse owners offer both free-choice loose salt and a salt block. Electrolyte supplements may be needed for horses in heavy work." },
  { question: "What is the forage-to-grain ratio for horses?", answer: "The ideal forage-to-grain ratio depends on the horse's workload. At maintenance, the diet should be nearly 100% forage with minimal or no grain. Light work calls for about 80-85% forage and 15-20% grain. Moderate work shifts to 70-75% forage and 25-30% grain. Heavy work may be 60-65% forage and 35-40% grain. Even in high-performance horses, forage should never drop below 50% of total intake to prevent digestive issues like gastric ulcers and hindgut acidosis." }
]) %>

